http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: The History Standards describe what students should know and be able to do at third through twelfth grade. They reflect an understanding of historical events and the application of historical thinking skills in viewing the human record. These academic standards provide an organizing content for schools.
Historical Analysis and Skills Development
Continuity and Change over Time
Identify a sequence of events through a day.
Identify chronological sequence through days, weeks, months, and years (calendar time).
Demonstrate an understanding of chronology.
Read and interpret information on simple timelines.
Identify the difference between past, present and future using timelines and/or other graphic representations.
Fact/Opinion and Points of View
With guidance and support, differentiate facts from opinions as related to an event.
Identify a problem or dilemma surrounding an event.
Identify documents relating to an event.
Identify fact, opinion, multiple points of view, and primary sources as related to historical events.
Research
Understand that information comes from many sources such as books, computers, and newspapers.
Explain how to locate information in a source.
Identify sources of historical information.
Apply sources of historical information.
Conduct teacher guided inquiry on assigned topics using specified historical sources. (Reference RWSL Standard 1.8.3 Research)
Pennsylvania History
Contributions from Individuals and Groups (PA)
Identify people in authority.
Identify groups of people who contribute to a community.
Identify historical figures in the local community.
Identify the social, political, cultural, and economic contributions of individuals and groups from Pennsylvania.
Historical Documents, Artifacts, and Places (PA)
Examine photographs of documents, artifacts, and paces unique to Pennsylvania.
Identify symbols, slogans, or mottos that are representative of the state.
Identify important buildings, statutes, and monuments associated with the state's history.
Identify historical documents, artifacts, and places critical to Pennsylvania history. Locate historical documents, artifacts, and places critical to Pennsylvania history.
Impact of Continnity and Change on PA History
Identify holiday and cultural celebrations in a community and why they are celebrated.
Identify how commerce and industry and social organizations have changed over time in Pennsylvania.

Identify and describe how continuity and change have impacted Pennsylvania history.
  • Belief systems and religions
  • Commerce and industry
  • Technology
  • Politics and government
  • Physical and human geography
  • Social organizations
Conflict and Cooperation (PA)
Demonstrate an understanding of conflict.
Identify historical conflict in the community.
Identify how conflict is impacted by ethnicity and race, working conditions, immigration, military conflict, and economics.

Identify and describe how conflict and cooperation among groups and organizations have impacted the history and development of Pennsylvania.
  • Ethnicity and race
  • Working conditions
  • Immigration
  • Military conflict
  • Economic stability
United States History
Contributions of Individuals and Groups (US History)
Identify American people related to national holidays.
Identify Americans who played a significant role in American history.
Identify groups and organizations and their contributions to the United States.
Identify and describe the social, political, cultural, and economic contributions of individuals and groups in United States history.
Historical Documents and Artifacts (US History)
Identify documents and artifacts important to the classroom community.
Identify American landmarks and their significance.
Identify American artifacts and their importance in American history.
Identify and describe historical documents, artifacts, and places critical to United States history.
Impact of Continuity and Change on US History
Demonstrate an understanding of time order.
Identify examples of change.
Identify facts related to how different people describe the same event at different time periods.
Demonstrate an understanding of how people in different times and places view the world.
Conflict and Cooperation (United States)
Identify conflict and describe ways to cooperate with others by making smart choices.
Demonstrate an understanding of how different groups describe the same event or situation.

Identify and describe how conflict and cooperation among groups and organizations have impacted the history and development of the US.
  • Ethnicity and race
  • Working conditions
  • Immigration
  • Military conflict
  • Economic stability
World History
Contributions of Individuals and Groups (World)
Explain how cultures celebrate.
Explain why cultures celebrate.
Explain why cultures have commemorations and remembrances.
Identify the elements of culture and ethnicity.
Historical Documents, Artifacts, and Sites (World)
Explain the importance of world landmarks.
Explain the significance of historical documents on world history.
Examine the effects of selected artifacts, historical documents, and related sites on the world.
Impact of Continuity and Change (World)
Identify different celebrations of different cultures from around the world.
Identify holidays and ceremonies of selected world cultures.
Identify how cultures have commemorations and remembrances.
Compare and contrast selected world cultures.
Conflict and Cooperation (World)
Demonstrate an understanding of conflict and cooperation.
Describe examples of conflict and cooperation in the classroom community.
Identify global issues that require cooperation among nations.
Identify conflict and cooperation among groups and organizations from around the world.
